from pyspark.sql import functions as F
from pyspark.sql.functions import array_contains,col

# change this line of code
null = []
weekend_friendliness = US.select('city', 'Hours', 'business_id', F.when((US['Hours']['Sunday'].isNotNull()) &\
                                                         (US['Hours']['Saturday'].isNotNull()), 1).otherwise(0).alias('weekend'))

weekend_friendliness = weekend_friendliness.filter(((US['Hours']['Saturday'].isNull())&\
                                             (US['Hours']['Sunday'].isNull())&\
                                             (US['Hours']['Monday'].isNull())&\
                                             (US['Hours']['Tuesday'].isNull())&\
                                             (US['Hours']['Wednesday'].isNull())&\
                                             (US['Hours']['Thursday'].isNull())&\
                                             (US['Hours']['Friday'].isNull())) == False)
weekend_friendliness = weekend_friendliness.groupby('city')\
.agg((F.sum('weekend')/F.count('weekend')).alias('weekend_friendliness')).select('city', 'weekend_friendliness')

from pyspark.sql import functions as F
from pyspark.sql.functions import array_contains,col


nightlife_hotness = \
US.select(US['city'], F.when(array_contains(US['categories'], 'Nightlife'), 1).otherwise(0).alias('nightyes'))\
.groupby('city').agg((F.sum('nightyes')/F.count('nightyes')).alias('nightlife_hotness'))

Step 10c: What is your interpretation of the correlations?¶

My interpretation would be that, based on the weak positive correlation coefficient of nightlife_hotness to the other 2 factors, the nightlife scene of a city may be independent from weekend friendliness or reviews.

For the moderate negative correlation for weekend_friendliness and avg(stars), this may be caused by a difference in clientele of establishments in the weekend vs. weekdays, as well as potentially just number of reviews. It also may be that the weekend_friendliness measurement of a city does not reflect the quality of establishments, as worse restaurants may choose to stay open on the weekend to gain more sales.

It may be worth looking into number of reviews received by establishments, in terms of relation to star rating, and days open. If there is a strong correlation on the establishment level, it may indicate that the moderate correlation on average stars and weekend_friendliness in the city level may have a confounding variable.

Above and Beyond¶

My work can be considered for above and beyond credit for the following reasons:

  • 1st question integrates using pyspark in a python function for use in the select method for Pyspark Dataframes, as well as trying to rename columns to remove the sum(x) format used to fit jupyter notebook view.
  • 2nd question provides a geographic visualization of noise in Las Vegas, using Folium, in order to take advantage of data having latitude and longitude information

def newamb(amb):
    return F.when(US['attributes.Ambience.{}'.format(amb)] == True, 1).otherwise(0).alias(amb)

noiselevel = F.when(US['attributes']['Noise Level'] == 'quiet', 1)\
            .when(US['attributes']['Noise Level'] == 'average', 2)\
            .when(US['attributes']['Noise Level'] == 'loud', 3)\
            .when(US['attributes']['Noise Level'] == 'very_loud', 4).otherwise(0).alias('noise')

import folium
vegasmap = folium.Map(location=[36.12, -115.15], zoom_start=11)
colormap = {1:'green', 2:'yellow', 3:'orange', 4:'red'}
for x, y in noiseloc[noiseloc.noise != 2].iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(location=[y['latitude'], y['longitude']], color = colormap[y['noise']], radius=2).add_to(vegasmap)
